International Tributes to the History of Flight
= Henri Farman Breaks the One-Minute Barrier =
A former artist and racecar driver, Henri Farman pur-
chased his first powered aircraft, a Voisin biplane, in
the early 1900's. Then he set about to make major
alterations to it, thus developing the aircraft that be-
came known as the Voisin-Farman I.
After a series of successful tests, Farman took off
in his biplane from Issy-les-Moulineaux, outside of
Paris, on November 9, 1907. As the amazed onlookers
cheered and waved, the plane completed a circuit of
3,380 feet. Even more important, it stayed in the air
for a full 74 seconds — 15 seconds longer than the
previous duration record set by the Wright brothers
in 1903. The one-minute barrier was broken at last.
The full-color cachet pictures the Voisin-Farman I
in flight. Among the extensive modifications Farman
made to the plane before his milestone flight were
the removal of the vertical panels between the wings
and the improvement of the tail surfaces and land-
ing gear.
Mint Stamp: The mint stamp on this Cover was issued
by Rwanda in 1978. It shows Henri Farman and his
Voisin-Farman I in which he achieved another mile-
stone in 1908 - the first officially logged flight of
more than one kilometer.
Postmark: This Cover was postmarked in Paris, France
on November 9, 1985, the exact anniversary of the
first European flight of more than one minute.
